  "text": "Grafana's API key authentication and scope enforcement is implemented through a multi-layered system:\n\n## API Key Authentication Middleware\n\nThe primary authentication client is implemented in `pkg/services/authn/clients/api_key.go`. The `Authenticate()` method (line 58) serves as the entry point for API key validation. This method:\n1. Extracts the token from the HTTP Authorization header (Bearer token format or basic auth with api_key username)\n2. Decodes and validates the token using `getAPIKey()` (line 92)\n3. Validates the API key using `validateApiKey()` (line 212)\n4. Returns an identity based on the linked service account\n\n## Key Validation Logic\n\nThe `validateApiKey()` function (line 212 in api_key.go) implements three critical security checks:\n1. **Expiration Check (line 213)**: `if key.Expires != nil && *key.Expires <= time.Now().Unix()` - Rejects expired keys with `errAPIKeyExpired`\n2. **Revocation Check (line 217)**: `if key.IsRevoked != nil && *key.IsRevoked` - Rejects revoked keys with `errAPIKeyRevoked`\n3. **Organization Check (line 221)**: `if orgID != key.OrgID` - Enforces organization isolation with `errAPIKeyOrgMismatch`\n4. **Service Account Requirement (line 226)**: Validates that API keys are linked to service accounts, as plain API keys are deprecated\n\n## Data Storage and Retrieval\n\nAPI keys are persisted in the database via `pkg/services/apikey/apikeyimpl/xorm_store.go`:\n- `GetAPIKeyByHash()` (line 89) - Retrieves API key by its hashed value for authentication\n- `GetApiKeyByName()` (line 72) - Retrieves API key by name (used for legacy API keys)\n- `AddAPIKey()` (line 33) - Creates new API keys with optional expiration\n- `UpdateAPIKeyLastUsedDate()` (line 103) - Tracks API key usage for audit purposes\n\nThe data model in `pkg/services/apikey/model.go` defines the APIKey struct with:\n- `Expires` field: Unix timestamp for key expiration\n- `IsRevoked` field: Boolean flag for revocation status\n- `ServiceAccountId` field: Link to the associated service account for permission inheritance\n- `OrgID` field: Organization isolation\n\n## Scope and Permission Enforcement\n\nAPI key scopes are enforced through service account permissions. When an API key is authenticated:\n1. The linked service account ID is retrieved from the APIKey object\n2. In gRPC contexts (`pkg/services/grpcserver/interceptors/auth.go` line 107), the service account is fetched via `GetSignedInUser()` using the service account ID\n3. Permissions are loaded via `AccessControlService.GetUserPermissions()` (line 131)\n4. Scopes are grouped by action using `accesscontrol.GroupScopesByActionContext()` (line 135)\n5. API requests are then evaluated against these scopes for authorization\n\n## Token Generation and Validation\n\nThe authentication flow supports both modern service account tokens and legacy API keys:\n- Modern tokens use `satokengen.Decode()` to decode service account tokens\n- Legacy API keys use `apikeygen.Decode()` and signature validation\n- Both token types are validated via hash comparison against stored values\n\n## Request Context Initialization\n\nThe `pkg/services/contexthandler/contexthandler.go` middleware initializes the request context with authentication information, determining whether the request is authenticated via API key (type `claims.TypeAPIKey`) or service account (`claims.TypeServiceAccount`).\n\n## Key Security Features\n\n1. **Expiration Management**: API keys can be created with a `SecondsToLive` parameter (validated in xorm_store.go line 43-48) which sets the expiration timestamp\n2. **Last Used Tracking**: The `Hook()` method (line 158 in api_key.go) asynchronously updates the last used timestamp for audit trails\n3. **Revocation Support**: Keys can be revoked without deletion, maintaining audit history\n4. **Organization Isolation**: Keys are scoped to organizations, preventing cross-org access\n5. **Service Account Binding**: Modern API keys inherit all permissions from their linked service account, enabling fine-grained access control\n"
}

